### Common Pitfalls

| Wrong | Right |
|-------|-------|
| `fn foo()` | `fun foo()` |
| `foo() -> int` | `foo() : int` |
| `s[n..m]` slice syntax (dots) | **Parse error with targeted message** — use colons: `s[n:m]`, `s[n:]`, `s[:m]`. hica now emits: *"slice separator must be a colon, not `..` — write `s[n:m]`, not `s[n..m]`"*. `..` is only valid in list spread patterns `[x, ..rest]`. |
| `if cond then expr else other` | `then` is NOT a keyword in hica — parse error. Use brace syntax: `if cond { expr } else { other }`. |
| `return x` or `return Err(e)` anywhere in a function | hica has NO `return` keyword — it is a parse error. The last expression is the return value. For early error propagation in parsers, use **nested `match` chains**: `match foo() { Err(e) => Err(e), Ok(v) => /* rest of function — this IS the return value */ }`. Alternatively use `and_then_result`: `foo() \|> and_then_result((v) => ...)`. Never write `return Err(e)` inside a match arm. |
| `let (a, b) = result_expr` — destructuring a result as a tuple | `result<(a,b), e>` is a `result`, not a tuple. You cannot destructure it with `let (a, b) = ...`. Use `match result_expr { Ok((a, b)) => ..., Err(e) => Err(e) }` instead. **Most common case**: you write a `collect_items` helper that returns `result<(list<T>, int), string>`, then the caller does `let (items, pos) = collect_items(s, p, [])` — type error. Fix: `match collect_items(s, p, []) { Ok((items, pos)) => ..., Err(e) => Err(e) }`. This is separate from the closing-delimiter check: always pattern match the result before accessing the cursor position. |
| `"a" ++ "b"` | `"a" + "b"` |
| `str(n)` | `show(n)` |
| `else { () }` | `else { }` |
| `my-variable` | `my_variable` |
| `assert(x \|> f == val)` | `let r = x \|> f; assert(r == val)` |
| `assert(match ...)` | `let r = match ...; assert(r == ...)` |
| `items[i]` (list index) | recursive pattern match |
| `let rec aux(x) = ... in aux(start)` (local recursive function) | hica has NO local recursive functions and NO `let ... in` syntax. Every recursive helper must be a top-level `fun`. Pass all needed state as explicit arguments. This is the single most common mistake when generating parsers or tree traversals. |
| inner `fun` closing over outer param for recursion | pass state as an explicit accumulator argument to a top-level helper |
| `(j, _) =>` tuple destructuring in a lambda param | NOT supported — same rule as `fun swap((a,b))`. Destructure in the body: `(pair) => { match pair { (j, _) => j } }` |
| `tok.value` field access on an enum variant | enums require pattern matching, not dot notation. `TokNum(n)` → `match tok { TokNum(n) => n, _ => 0.0 }` |
| `"prefix" ++ rest` as a match pattern | String concatenation patterns like `"hello" ++ rest` are NOT valid match patterns in hica. However, plain string literals ARE valid match patterns: `Some("n") => ...`, `"n" => ...`, `match ch { "n" => ..., "t" => ... }` all work. Exception: `"{"` and `"}"` trigger string interpolation — use `"\{"` and `"\}"` instead (see the brace interpolation pitfall). **Correct approach for single-char dispatch**: string literal patterns in match arms work directly. `Some("t") => parse_literal(c, "true", JBool(true))` is valid. |
| `split(s, "")` to get individual characters | splitting by empty string does NOT yield characters in hica. For character-level parsing, iterate by building a cursor index or use `split` on a non-empty separator |
| `c >= "0" and c <= "9"` comparing single-char strings | string comparison operators `<`/`>` are not defined on strings in hica. Use `contains` or `starts_with` for character checks |
| `a and b`, `a or b` (word-form boolean operators) | hica uses `&&` and `\|\|` only: `a && b`, `a \|\| b`. `and`/`or` are plain identifiers and will cause a parse error when used as infix operators. |
| `Ok(value, cursor)` — `Ok` with two arguments | `Ok` takes exactly ONE argument. Return a tuple: `Ok((value, cursor))`. Getting this wrong causes a type error that looks like an arity mismatch. |
| Calling any sub-parser directly inside `parse_value` without wrapping in a Json constructor | `parse_value` returns `result<(Json, int), string>`. Any sub-parser that returns a more specific type — `parse_string_val` → `result<(string,int),string>`, `parse_number` → `result<(float,int),string>` — must be wrapped. Use explicit match: `match parse_string_val(c) { Ok((str, nc)) => Ok((JString(str), nc)), Err(e) => Err(e) }`. Same rule for `parse_array` → `JArray(...)`, `parse_object` → `JObject(...)`, `parse_number` → `JNumber(...)`. Do NOT use `map_result` with a match lambda here — it generates a Koka layout error (see the `map_result` codegen pitfall above). |
| `Ok(([], pos))` when `s[pos:]` starts with `"]"` or `"}"` | Does NOT consume the closing bracket — `pos` still points at `]` or `}`. The outer caller sees trailing content and returns an error. Always advance past the bracket: `Ok(([], pos + 1))`. |
| `buf + peek(cur) \|> unwrap_or("")` — `|>` precedence with `+` | `|>` has very low precedence and binds last. This parses as `(buf + peek(cur)) \|> unwrap_or("")` — wrong. Wrap the piped expression in parens or use a `let`: `let ch = peek(cur) \|> unwrap_or(""); buf + ch` |
| `{ ...p, score: p.score + 1 }` (struct spread) | NOT supported — reconstruct fully: `Player { score: p.score + 1, name: p.name }` |
| `show(x)` inside `"...{show(x)}..."` with generic `x` | Koka can't resolve `show` overload for unconstrained type — use `"{x}"` directly (interpolation calls show implicitly), or annotate the parameter type |
| Claiming list match functions are polymorphic when they use `show` | `show(x)` requires a concrete type — add a type annotation e.g. `xs: list<int>` when using `show` on elements |
| `fun swap((a, b)) => (b, a)` (tuple param destructuring) | NOT supported — parse error. Destructure inside the body: `fun swap(pair) { match pair { (a, b) => (b, a) } }` |
| `is_empty(xs)` on a list | **Fixed** — `is_empty` is now overloaded: works on both `string` and `list<T>`. `is_empty([])` returns `true`. |
| `head(xs)` as an `int` seed value | `head` returns `maybe<T>` not `T` — use `match xs { [] => 0, [x, ..rest] => ... }` or `head_or(xs, 0)` from `std/list` |
| `type Cursor = (string, int)` (type alias) | hica has NO type aliases. `type X = Y` is not valid syntax. Use a named `struct` instead: `struct Cursor { s: string, pos: int }`, or just pass tuples directly without naming them. |
| `c1.pos` — named field access on a tuple | Tuples only support positional access: `.0`, `.1`, `.2`. Named field access requires a `struct`. If you used `type Cursor = (string, int)`, the field `pos` does not exist — use `c1.1` or refactor to `struct Cursor { s: string, pos: int }` and access `c1.pos`. |
| `s[n..m]` slice syntax (dots instead of colon) | **Parse error** — hica uses colon syntax for slices: `s[n:m]`, `s[n:]`, `s[:m]`. `..` inside `[ ]` is valid ONLY as a range literal `[lo..hi]` (both sides must be expressions, not a slice of an existing variable). `s[n..m]` is still a parse error — write `s[n:m]`. Every `s[pos..pos+1]` in a parser must be written `s[pos:pos+1]`. |
| `contains("charset_string", s[n:])` to check a multi-char slice against a set | `contains(haystack, needle)` checks if `needle` is a **substring** of `haystack`. When `needle` is a multi-character slice (e.g. `s[4:]`), this almost always returns false even when the intent is to check if the first character is in the set. Always extract a single character first: `contains("abcdef...", s[4:5])`. |
| Returning a cursor pointing AT a closing delimiter without consuming it | When a recursive string/array/object parser sees the closing character and returns, the cursor still points AT it. The next parser step then sees a stray delimiter. Fix: always return the position PAST the closing char (`pos + 1` or `advance(c, 1)`). **Applies to ALL delimiters — `"`, `]`, `}`**. Most common mistake in string parsers: `"\"" => Ok((acc, pos))` — should be `Ok((acc, pos + 1))`. In object parsers, if `parse_string_content` returns position AT the closing `"`, the caller then does `skip_ws(s, key_end)` which sees `"` instead of `:` and returns `Err("expected ':'")` for every object. |
| `parse_number` returning `float` instead of `Json` when used inside `parse_value`, and ALL other sub-parsers with mismatched inner types | `parse_value` returns `result<(Json, int), string>`. **Every** sub-parser that returns a different inner type must be wrapped. This applies to ALL FOUR cases simultaneously — the most common mistake is wrapping the "obvious" ones (string, number) and forgetting the "obvious" collection ones (array, object): `parse_string_val` → `result<(string, int), string>` needs `JString`; `parse_number` → `result<(float, int), string>` needs `JNumber`; `parse_array` → `result<(list<Json>, int), string>` needs `JArray`; `parse_object` → `result<(list<(string,Json)>, int), string>` needs `JObject`. Only `parse_literal` returns `result<(Json, int), string>` directly. The failure mode for forgetting `parse_array`/`parse_object` is: the match arm type-unifies `list<Json>` with `Json`, causing the ENTIRE `parse_value` match to fail with cascading mismatches. Explicit wrap pattern for all four:
```
Some("\"") => match parse_string_val(s, p) { Ok((str, np)) => Ok((JString(str), np)), Err(e) => Err(e) },
Some("[")  => match parse_array(s, p) { Ok((items, np)) => Ok((JArray(items), np)), Err(e) => Err(e) },
Some("\{") => match parse_object(s, p) { Ok((fields, np)) => Ok((JObject(fields), np)), Err(e) => Err(e) },
Some(ch) if contains("0123456789-", ch) => match parse_number(s, p) { Ok((n, np)) => Ok((JNumber(n), np)), Err(e) => Err(e) },
``` |
| No whitespace skip after commas in array/object recursive helpers | When `parse_array_rest(s, ws + 1, acc)` is called after finding a comma at position `ws`, `ws + 1` points to the character immediately after the comma — which may be a space. If `parse_value` doesn't skip leading whitespace, `[1, 2]` will fail because `parse_value` sees `" 2"` and hits the error arm. **Fix**: always skip whitespace before calling `parse_value`: `let next = skip_ws(s, ws + 1); parse_array_rest(s, next, acc)` or call `skip_ws` at the top of `parse_array_rest`/`parse_object_rest`. |
| `ch if is_digit(ch)` guard in `match peek(s, p)` — `ch` captures `maybe<string>`, not `string` | In `match peek(s, p)` the scrutinee is `maybe<string>`. A bare variable pattern `ch` captures the entire `maybe<string>` value. Writing `ch if is_digit(ch)` fails because `is_digit` expects `string` but `ch` has type `maybe<string>`. **Fix**: use `Some(ch)` to destructure and bind the inner string: `Some(ch) if is_digit(ch) => parse_number(s, p)`. The same rule applies to any guard that operates on the inner value — always match with the constructor first. |
| `s[c.pos:c.pos+1]` instead of `c.s[c.pos:c.pos+1]` in `peek` | When defining `fun peek(c: Cursor) : maybe<string>`, the string field is `c.s`, not `s`. Writing `Some(s[c.pos:c.pos+1])` references an undefined variable `s`. This causes a cascade of type errors: `length` infers `list<t>` instead of `string`, breaking every downstream type inference including the import of `Json` constructors. The fix is simply `Some(c.s[c.pos:c.pos+1])`. |
| Numbers not handled in `parse_value` — `parse_number` written but never called | `parse_value` dispatches on the first character. If there is no `Some("-")` or `Some(ch) if is_digit(ch)` arm, numbers fall through to the `_` arm and return an error. `parse_number` may be correctly implemented but completely unreachable. Always include explicit number arms: `Some("-") => ...`, `Some(ch) if is_digit(ch) => ...`, or `Some(ch) if contains("0123456789-", ch) => ...`. |
| `parse_array_rest` / `parse_object_rest` first element never parsed | A common structural mistake: `parse_array` skips whitespace after `[`, finds a non-`]` character, and calls `parse_array_rest(s, next, [])` where `next` points AT the first element. But if `parse_array_rest` only has arms for `]` (return acc) and `,` (consume separator then parse), the first element hits the `_` arm and returns `Err("expected ',' or ']'")` — every non-empty array fails immediately. Same bug in `parse_object_rest`. **Fix**: the recursive helper must ALWAYS try to parse a value first, THEN check for `,` or terminator:
```
fun parse_array_items(s, pos, acc) {
  let p = skip_ws(s, pos)
  match peek(s, p) {
    Some("]") => Ok((reverse(acc), p + 1)),
    _ => match parse_value(s, p) {
      Ok((item, np)) => {
        let wp = skip_ws(s, np)
        match peek(s, wp) {
          Some(",") => parse_array_items(s, wp + 1, [item] + acc),
          Some("]") => Ok((reverse([item] + acc), wp + 1)),
          _         => Err("expected ',' or ']'")
        }
      },
      Err(e) => Err(e)
    }
  }
}
``` |
| Dropping the last parsed item from an accumulator when the closing delimiter is found | When using a two-phase pattern (collector stops at `,`; caller handles `]`/`}`), the `_` arm of the inner `match peek` fires when the next char is `]` or `}` — at that point `acc` must STILL include the just-parsed item. The fix applies in TWO places: (1) when dispatching on `,` vs `]`/`}` AFTER a successful parse — `_ => Ok((acc, pos))` should be `_ => Ok(([item] + acc, pos))`; (2) when the collector sees the closing delimiter at the TOP of its loop (before parsing any item), return `acc` as-is — that case is correct since no item was parsed. Concrete fix pattern:
```
// WRONG — last item dropped
Some(ch) if ch == "," => collect_items(s, pos+1, [item] + acc),
_ => Ok((acc, pos))          // item not in acc!
// RIGHT
Some(ch) if ch == "," => collect_items(s, pos+1, [item] + acc),
_ => Ok(([item] + acc, pos)) // item included
``` |
| `json_str(json_get(j, "key"))` when `json_get` returns `maybe<Json>` | `json_str` takes `Json`, not `maybe<Json>`. This is a type error. Compose with `and_then`: `json_get(j, "key") \|> and_then(json_str)` or match explicitly: `match json_get(j, "key") { Some(v) => json_str(v), None => None }`. |
| `f.0` and `f.1` tuple field access in a lambda over generic pairs | `.0`/`.1` on generic tuples emits ambiguous `.fst`/`.snd` in Koka and may fail to typecheck. Destructure with `match` in the lambda body instead: `(pair) => match pair { (a, b) => ... }`. **Most common manifestation**: wrapping a sub-parser result in a Json constructor — `parse_number(s, p) \|> map_result((pair) => (JNumber(pair.0), pair.1))` is wrong. Correct: `parse_number(s, p) \|> map_result((pair) => match pair { (n, pos) => (JNumber(n), pos) })`. |
| `r \|> and_then((x) => ...)` when `r` is `result<T,E>` | `and_then` is for `maybe<T>` only. For `result<T,E>`, use `and_then_result(r, (x) => ...)` or `r \|> and_then_result((x) => ...)`. Mixing them causes a type mismatch that looks like a unification error. |
| `r \|> and_then_result((x) => ...)` when `r` is `maybe<T>` | `and_then_result` is for `result<T,E>` only. For `maybe<T>`, use `and_then(m, (x) => ...)` or `m \|> and_then((x) => ...)`. Using `and_then_result` on a `maybe` is a type error. Functions like `json_str`, `json_array`, `json_get`, `parse_int`, `parse_float`, `head` all return `maybe<T>` — chain them with `and_then`, not `and_then_result`. |
| `map_result(plain_value, f)` where `plain_value` is not a `result<T,E>` | `map_result` takes a `result<T,E>` as its first argument. Calling `map_result(head_or(xs, default), f)` fails because `head_or` returns `T`, not `result<T,E>`. If you want to map a plain value, just call `f(value)` directly or use `let x = head_or(xs, default); f(x)`. |
| `r \|> map_result((pair) => match pair { (a, b) => Ok((T, b)) })` — returning `Ok(...)` inside `map_result`'s lambda | The lambda argument to `map_result` must return the **plain success value**, not a `result`. `map_result(r, f)` applies `f: A -> B` to the unwrapped value and re-wraps it, giving `result<B, E>`. If `f` returns `Ok(v)` (i.e. `f: A -> result<B,E>`), the whole expression becomes `result<result<B,E>, E>` — a type error. **Correct**: `r \|> map_result((pair) => match pair { (str, pos) => (JString(str), pos) })`. **Wrong**: `r \|> map_result((pair) => match pair { (str, pos) => Ok((JString(str), pos)) })`. If you need the lambda to return a result (e.g. for validation), use `and_then_result` instead. |
| Sub-parser result used directly in `parse_value` without wrapping in a Json constructor | `parse_value` returns `result<(Json, int), string>`. Sub-parsers like `parse_array` return `result<(list<Json>, int), string>` and `parse_number` returns `result<(float, int), string>` — different types. You must wrap with explicit match: `match parse_array(c) { Ok((items, nc)) => Ok((JArray(items), nc)), Err(e) => Err(e) }`. Writing `parse_array(c) \|> map_result((pair) => Ok(pair))` has TWO bugs: the `Ok()` wrapping AND missing `JArray(...)`. Note: do NOT use `map_result` with a match lambda here — it generates a Koka layout error. |
| `match r { Ok(v) => v, Err(e) => Err(e) }` where the intent is to "unwrap or re-wrap" | `Ok(v) => v` returns `T` (the unwrapped value), while `Err(e) => Err(e)` returns `result<T,E>` — the two branches have different types and the match fails to typecheck. If `r` is already a `result` and you want to propagate it unchanged, just use `r` directly. If you want to transform the `Ok` case, use `map_result(r, (v) => ...)`. If you want to propagate errors in a chain, use `and_then_result`. Never write a match just to echo the two constructors back. |
| `json_get(j, "")` or `json_get(j, "key")` on a non-object `Json` value | `json_get` does object key lookup — it returns `None` when `j` is anything other than `JObject(...)`. To extract a top-level string, use `json_str(j)` directly. For a top-level array, use `json_array(j)`. For a top-level number, use `json_num(j)`. Only use `json_get` when `j` is an object and you want a field by name. |
| `unwrap_maybe_or(json_get(j, "key"), "string_default")` | `json_get` returns `maybe<Json>`. The second argument to `unwrap_maybe_or` must match the inner type — `Json`, not `string`. `unwrap_maybe_or(json_get(j, "name"), "unknown")` is a type error because `"unknown" : string` but the expected default is `Json`. To get a string default: chain through `json_str` first — `json_get(j, "name") \|> and_then(json_str) \|> unwrap_maybe_or("unknown")`. |
| `unwrap_or(maybe_value, default)` on a `maybe<T>` | `unwrap_or` is for `result<T,E>` (returns the value if `Ok`, or `default` if `Err`). For `maybe<T>`, use `unwrap_maybe_or(m, default)`. Using `unwrap_or` on a `maybe` is a type error. Pattern: `json_get(j, "k") \|> and_then(json_str) \|> unwrap_maybe_or("default")`. |
| `expr \|> match { Ok(x) => ..., Err(e) => ... }` | `match` requires a scrutinee — you cannot pipe directly into a bare `match` block. Write it as `match expr { Ok(x) => ..., Err(e) => ... }`. |
| `starts_with(s, " \t\n\r")` to check for whitespace | Checks for the literal 4-character string `" \t\n\r"`, not any whitespace character. Use separate `starts_with` calls: `starts_with(s, " ") \|\| starts_with(s, "\t") \|\| starts_with(s, "\n") \|\| starts_with(s, "\r")`. |
| Calling `id(42)` then `id("hello")` in the same function | Type inference monomorphizes within a single `fun` or `main` body: `id` locks to `int` at first call. However, each `test` block has its own independent scope, so calling `id(42)` and `id("hello")` in the *same test block* is valid. Never mix types within one `fun main()`. |
| Using a generic function in `main()` with one type AND in a test block with a different type | In `hica test` mode, all test blocks and `main()` share ONE type inference context. `swap(("a","b"))` in main constrains swap for ALL test blocks too. **Fix: omit `main()` from files that test generic functions across multiple types.** Put the usage example in a separate `.hc` file, or keep all types consistent across the whole file. `hica check` is more permissive and may not catch this. |
| Using helper functions like `fun demo_int() => id(42)` and `fun demo_str() => id("hello")` to work around monomorphism | Does NOT work — named top-level functions in the same file share the same inference context. `id` still gets locked to `int`. **Only `test` blocks get independent type inference scopes.** To test a generic with multiple types, use separate test blocks. |
| Calling `id(10)` then `id("hello")` in `main()` in a "separate" usage file | Still fails — `main()` is a top-level function and shares the file's inference context. `id` locks to `int` on the first call. **A generic function can only be used with ONE concrete type within a single `fun main()` body.** Split into multiple files if you need both. |
| `hica check` showing `[IO]` effect signatures | `hica check` reports only error count and top-level effects e.g. `[<console, fsys>]` — it does NOT print per-function effect types |
| Inconsistent opening-quote convention in string parser helpers | When `parse_string_inner` starts reading at the character AFTER the opening `"`, all callers must pass `pos + 1` (skipping the `"`). If `parse_value` calls `parse_string_val(s, p + 1)` but `parse_object_fields` calls `parse_string_val(s, p)` with `p` pointing AT `"`, then `parse_string_inner` sees `"` immediately and returns `Ok(("", p+1))` — an empty string for every object key. Pick ONE convention and apply it everywhere: either always pass the position AFTER the opening `"`, or have `parse_string_val` itself check and skip the `"` before calling the inner helper. |
| Bare `if` without `else` used as a guard clause expecting early exit | In a block body `{ ... }`, a bare `if cond { Err("...") }` statement **does NOT return early**. It evaluates to `Err(...)` (or `()` in the false branch), discards the value, and execution continues to the next statement. In hica there is no early return — the block returns its **last expression** only. This pattern silently drops all error paths. The fix is to use a single `if/else if/else` chain: `if cond1 { Err("...") } else if cond2 { Ok(...) } else { next_step }`. | In a block body `{ ... }`, a bare `if cond { Err("...") }` statement **does NOT return early**. It evaluates to `Err(...)` (or `()` in the false branch), discards the value, and execution continues to the next statement. In hica there is no early return — the block returns its **last expression** only. This pattern silently drops all error paths. The fix is to use a single `if/else if/else` chain: `if cond1 { Err("...") } else if cond2 { Ok(...) } else { next_step }`. Alternatively restructure with nested `match`. |
| Using a match-bound variable outside its match arm | A variable bound inside a match arm (`Ok(j) => { ... }`) is only in scope within that arm's body. After the `match` expression ends, `j` is out of scope. Attempting to use it after the match (e.g. `let emitted = json_emit(j)`) is a scope error. Fix: move the usage inside the arm, or bind the result of the match to an outer variable and handle both cases. |
| `r \|> map_result((pair) => match pair { (a, b) => ... })` | **Fixed** — `map_result` and `and_then_result` with a lambda containing a `match` expression now generate correct Koka layout. Both pipe styles work: `r \|> map_result((pair) => match pair { (a, b) => (J(a), b) })` and explicit `match r { Ok(x) => ..., Err(e) => Err(e) }`. |
| `"\b"` and `"\f"` in hica string literals | **Fixed** — hica now translates `\b` to `char_to_string(chr(8))` and `\f` to `char_to_string(chr(12))` in codegen. Both escape sequences work directly in string literals. |
| `"{"` or `"}"` as a string literal (including in match patterns like `Some("{")`) | hica's lexer treats `{` inside a double-quoted string as the START of string interpolation, and `}` as the END. Both cause parse errors. Writing `Some("{") =>` or `Some("}") =>` are both parse errors. **Fix**: always escape literal braces in ALL string contexts — match arms, error messages, comparisons: `Some("\{") =>` for `{` and `Some("\}") =>` for `}`. This applies even when the string appears inside a constructor pattern. **The specific parser case**: `Some("{") => parse_object(...)` is WRONG — use `Some("\{") => match parse_object(...) { Ok((fields, np)) => Ok((JObject(fields), np)), Err(e) => Err(e) }`. Models most commonly forget the escaping in match arms while correctly escaping it in error message strings in the same file. |
| `return Err(...)` keyword inside a function or match arm | hica has NO `return` keyword — it is a parse error. Every occurrence of `return expr` must be rewritten. In string/number parsers, the typical `return Err(...)` pattern is used for early exit from a while loop on invalid input. The fix is to restructure: use a recursive helper instead of a while loop, or use a `var err = None` flag and `break`, then check after the loop. Never write `return Err(e)` or `return Ok(v)` in any context. |
| `Err(...)` as a match arm body inside a `while` loop — value silently discarded | Inside a `while` loop body, every statement must produce `()` (unit). A match arm that returns `Err("invalid escape sequence")` produces `result<T,E>`, not `()`. The value is evaluated and immediately discarded — the loop continues, `p` never advances, causing an **infinite loop** on invalid input. This is the "no early return" problem applied specifically to while-loop match arms. Example wrong pattern:
```
while p < len {
  if ch == "\\" {
    match peek(s, p + 1) {
      Some("n") => { acc = acc + "\n"; p = p + 2 },
      _         => Err("invalid escape")  // ← WRONG: Err discarded, loop never exits
    }
  }
}
```
Fix options: (1) use a recursive helper instead of while — errors propagate naturally through the return type; (2) use `break` to exit the loop and return an error after: `var err: maybe<string> = None; while ... { if bad { err = Some("..."); break } ... }; match err { Some(e) => Err(e), None => Ok(...) }`. |
| Explicit return type annotation on a function containing `while` | **Fixed** — codegen now suppresses the return type annotation automatically when the function body contains `while`. You can write `fun skip_ws(c: Cursor) : Cursor { while ... }` and it compiles correctly. |
| `"expected '{'"` or `"expected ',' or '}'"` in error message strings — unescaped braces inside single-quoted text | `{` and `}` trigger string interpolation **anywhere** inside a double-quoted string, including inside single-quoted fragments within that string. `Err("expected '{'")` is a parse error because the `{` opens an interpolation. `Err("expected ',' or '}'")` is a parse error because `}` closes one. **Fix**: escape every literal brace in error messages too — `Err("expected '\{'")` and `Err("expected ',' or '\}'")`). This is the same rule as in match patterns but models frequently escape correctly in `Some("\{")` while forgetting to escape in the adjacent error strings in the same function. |
| Calling `skip_ws` inside a sub-parser that is always called after the caller has already skipped whitespace | When `parse_value` calls `skip_ws` and then dispatches to `parse_literal`, `parse_number`, etc., those helpers receive a position that is already past whitespace. If `parse_literal` also calls `skip_ws` internally it: (a) wastes work, and (b) introduces the `while`-loop `div` effect into an otherwise pure function, causing a Koka effect conflict. The Koka error looks like *"inferred effect: `<div\|_e>`, expected effect: `total`"*. **Fix**: keep leaf sub-parsers pure — call `skip_ws` only in the dispatcher (`parse_value`, `parse_json`) and pass an already-skipped position down. |

